# gen110 (L13+): prerequisites with conjunction and quantities. One sentence can
# teach several prerequisites ("X requires A and B"), and a prerequisite may carry
# a quantity ("batter requires 3 eggs"). The quantity is stored per requirer-step
# edge as amount(Goal, Step, N) and shown in the plan against the step that needs
# it. Still derived: the order is the topological sort, the amounts are recalled
# facts — nothing is a stored sentence.

# Conjunction: two prerequisites from one sentence.
> cake requires batter and oven
< Learned 2 prerequisites for cake.
# Conjunction WITH quantities: 3 eggs and 2 flour go into the batter.
> batter requires 3 eggs and 2 flour
< Learned 2 prerequisites for batter.
# The plan is ordered AND annotated: eggs/flour carry the amounts the batter
# needs; batter and oven (no amount given by cake) appear bare.
> how do I make cake?
< To make cake: 3 eggs, 2 flour, batter, oven, then cake.

# A single prerequisite sentence still reads the old way (backward compatible).
> oven requires gas
< Learned: requires(oven, gas).
> how do I make cake?
< To make cake: 3 eggs, 2 flour, batter, gas, oven, then cake.